In TypeScript, you can use the `Type` enum to specify a type system where you know the value may have multiple types but in practice, it will only have one. The `Type` enum provides a way to declare types with multiple possible values, but TypeScript will only enforce one of those types in a given context. Here's an example of how you can use the `Type` enum in TypeScript:

```typescript
